\pard\plain \tx0\tx360\tx720\tx1080\tx1440\tx1800\tx2160\tx2880\tx3600\tx4320\fi360\sl288\slmult1\ltrch\loch {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 Demons haunted the journey back through the temple. Their shadows lurked in every passage, spilled down staircases, hovered in the dark corners of rooms. One entire hall was packed with a wasp-paper hive, recently made; its cladding material\hich\f0 \emdash \loch\f0 compacted layers of regurgitated flesh. It burned brightly in the fulgent light of Mandri\loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8217\'92s fire. He only wished the whole temple was made of similar stuff. The place was infested. Demons ran amuck, mindlessly ambushing each other, and eating. Distant thumps and raging howls were a constant specter of death. They tried to ambush Mandri, but he could see their Sparks.}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 The Vessels directly behind him shuffled along, short swords drawn, ganging up to kill whatever he missed. Their frazzled nerves testified to their desperation. This ascent would bring them out of danger, and to die now, after everything, would be a great tragedy.}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 They kept their guard.}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 Eyes focused.}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 Breathing in nervous pants.}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 They amused Mandri.}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 Why they amused him was a interesting question, but not one he could entertain because his senses were nearer his skin. He wasn\loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8217\'92t accustomed to the uncomfortable heat in his throat. Then there was an oddness to how his toes squeezed inside his shoes, how his palm tingled as he braced against the stonework, how his legs moved without apparent effort. Most strange was his breathing; the sound of it was unfamiliar, as if it were someone else\u8217\'92s. Stray sensations is what they were, unwelcome and somehow demanding. They pushed him into an anxious malaise, which was a surreal experience considering the needs of the moment. He needed to be inside his eyes, searching the dark for demon Sparks.}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 He dispatched an enthusiastic lizard demon. It was no keenkedrin, but it did have a long body and long teeth. He watched it curl up against his heat, then realized why the Vessel\loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8217\'92s extreme focus amused him\hich\f0 \emdash \loch\f0 they feared completely different things than he did. Rightfully, they feared these demons.}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 What did he fear?}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 His own growling stomach.}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 He needed to eat.}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 Given current events, that seemed like a very dangerous thing for him to do. Almost sinful. }
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 Then there was Ayram. The giant gripped his spud-bar spear a little too tightly. He walked a little too far behind, careful to keep as many bodies between himself and Mandri as possible. There was suspicion in his face. And it didn\loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8217\'92t help that he was silent; he did not say a word through the whole of the dark, not until they\u8217\'92d battled all the way up to the temple\u8217\'92s wide entrance hall. Solraheen\u8217\'92s golden mask still sat atop the exit, inviting them outside. The Vessels rushed towards it.}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 \loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8220\'93No one leaves,\u8221\'94 Ayram growled.}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 The Vessels stopped in their tracks and turned, clearly concerned there\loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8217\'92d be one last battle. They looked to Mandri, hoping he was on their side.}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 \loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8220\'93My dear giant,\u8221\'94 Pyetle said, nonchalant, \u8220\'93This is not the place to idle.\u8221\'94}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 \loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8220\'93No one leaves,\u8221\'94 Ayram repeated. When he was sure that everyone would obey, he carried their attention over to the middle of the room. The body of the green robed prince still lay there on its side. Ayram studied the dead man, then poked around the large ash pit with his long spear. \u8220\'93Someone light a fire,\u8221\'94 he growled. \u8220\'93A big one. It will help keep the demons out.\u8221\'94}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 Pyetle walked to the opposite side of the firepit, picking his way around the small animal skeletons. \loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8220\'93Might I suggest that we put as much distance between us and this place as possible?\u8221\'94}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 \loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8220\'93There\u8217\'92s wood in a pile over there,\u8221\'94 Ayram said, nodding to a little alcove in the back of the hall. Moto moved to fetch a few logs. }
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 Pyetle cleared his throat. \loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8220\'93May I ask why we should not leave? Is this for our safety?\u8217\'92\u8221\'94}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 Ayram stared at Mandri. \loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8220\'93We need to talk.\u8221\'94}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 Mandri licked his teeth and said, \loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8220\'93I know.\u8221\'94 }
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 Moto set a few logs down into the ash pit, careful not to kick up a cloud. Ayram gave an impatient look to the Vessel who held the torch. Bidden, the man lent his torchfire to the logs, and in a flash, they were burning.}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 The resin-rich wood had a pleasing scent. It was some kind of ritual wood, Mandri supposed, seasoned for Solraheen\loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8217\'92s pleasure. Hopefully, it would keep the demons at bay. Moto set two more logs on top of the twisting flames, and this triggered a flash of light which let Mandri see the face of the green robed prince clearly. The man\u8217\'92s eyes were open. The eyewhites were rusted red. The rigid brow gave them a look of torment.}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 Ayram sat down next to that look of torment. He bade Mandri to sit across from it, and Mandri did.}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 \loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8220\'93Anyone have anything to eat?\u8221\'94 Mandri asked. }
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 Pyetle retrieved two small bricks of cappash from a Vessel. Cappash was a dried and minced lizard meat spiced with bitter herbs and caked in yellowed fat. He sat down on Mandri\loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8217\'92s right, at the dead prince\u8217\'92s feet, then handed a cappash brick to Mandri. \u8220\'93You look like you need it.\u8221\'94}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 Mandri accepted the offering. He nibbled on a corner, thinking there\loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8217\'92d be no taste. At first there wasn\u8217\'92t, but the second chew saw the meat\u8217\'92s smoky flavor percolate into being. It was not entirely enjoyable.}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 \loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8220\'93Sol\u8217\'92s light, I\u8217\'92m tired,\u8221\'94 he mumbled between mouthfuls. \u8220\'93I don\u8217\'92t suppose we could take some time to sleep? Perhaps take turns?\u8221\'94}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 Moto stole the other cappash brick out of Pyetle\loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8217\'92s hand, then sat down on Mandri\u8217\'92s left. \u8220\'93I didn\u8217\'92t know a Mazid needs to eat,\u8221\'94 he said.}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 \loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8220\'93That\u8217\'92s because he\u8217\'92s not a Mazid,\u8221\'94 Ayram grumbled. \u8220\'93Not anymore. Schisol\u8217\'92s own shadow named him the Burshageet.\u8221\'94 He paused to let the accusation breathe. Now that it was out the air it was its own kind of beast. It had horns. It to be dealt with.}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 \loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8220\'93What?\u8221\'94 Moto asked. \u8220\'93You think }{\f1\fs24\b0\i1 he\loch\af1\hich\af1\dbch\af1\uc1\u8217\'92s}{\f0\fs24\b0\i0  the Burshageet? Not a chance. Besides, it doesn\loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8217\'92t matter. Let it all burn. We are }{\f1\fs24\b0\i1 done}{\f0\fs24\b0\i0 .\loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8221\'94}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 Ayram grunted. \loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8220\'93This will not be finished until that boy is dead.\u8221\'94}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 \loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8220\'93Now, now,\u8221\'94 Pyetle said, a little ruffled. \u8220\'93We are all on the same side. Don\u8217\'92t let the words of that Black witch work you up. She was not a trustworthy source of information. She did come flying out of Shis, after all.\u8221\'94}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 \loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8220\'93Her words needs accounting,\u8221\'94 Ayram argued. \u8220\'93The boy\u8217\'92s stomach growls. Look at him eat.\u8221\'94}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 Mandri had shoved the hard cappash into his mouth with wringing hands. His teeth were sunk into its packed meat. He could taste the fat on his tongue. It was all bit messy, slobbering as he was, but he was truly hungry. He hadn\loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8217\'92t eaten in forever.}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 He pulled the brick out of his mouth and held it up for Ayram. \loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8220\'93Did you want some?\u8221\'94}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 Ayram grimaced as though he were offered human flesh.}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 \loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8220\'93Oh, come on,\u8221\'94 Mandri said. \u8220\'93I\u8217\'92ve done nothing to deserve that look. If it weren\u8217\'92t for me, you\u8217\'92d be dead.\u8221\'94}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 \loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8220\'93If you it weren\u8217\'92t for you, Elrahet would still be alive.\u8221\'94}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 Mandri scoffed, and for the first time \loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8220\'93You can\u8217\'92t know that.\u8221\'94 }
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 \loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8220\'93May I suggest,\u8221\'94 Pyetle said, adopting pious airs, \u8220\'93that we take honest stock of our situation? From where I sit, I see in Mandri a gift from Solraheen. I have faith that He\hich\f0 \emdash \loch\f0 \u8221\'94}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 \loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8220\'93Solraheen is dead,\u8221\'94 Ayram grumbled. \u8220\'93He has nothing to do with this.\u8221\'94}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 \loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8220\'93Then why does Mandri bear His fire? You all watched him turn back the hordes of Shis. Now you want to murder him for it?\u8221\'94 he leaned forward, suddenly convicted by his own argument. \u8220\'93He could kill us all, right this very moment, but he chooses not to! What crime has he committed?\u8221\'94}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 His question went unanswered, and of  it, Ayram stewed. Looked to the dead prince. He seemed to find something in the prince\loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8217\'92s empty gaze. He glared at thro. \u8220\'93Give me a reason not to kill you.\u8221\'94}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 Scoff. A few vessels behind, wondering what in gods name was happening.}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 Mandri \loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8220\'93I feel like the fact that you\u8217\'92re still alive should be reason enough. And why assume that you could kill me? I don\u8217\'92t think you can. Not of this matters, because you won\u8217\'92t.\u8221\'94}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 \loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8220\'93I won\u8217\'92t?\u8221\'94}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 \loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8220\'93You\u8217\'92re not going to kill me. You won\u8217\'92t try. Not tonight, at least. Perhaps tomorrow. I don\u8217\'92t know.\u8221\'94}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 Ayram\loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8217\'92s disdain deepened. His face twisted up. \u8220\'93That black witch disemboweled herself for what she saw in the future. The question which worries me is: why would she kill herself, unless she was certain that }{\f1\fs24\b0\i1 you }{\f0\fs24\b0\i0 was going to finish her work?\loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8221\'94}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 \loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8220\'93I see what\u8217\'92s happening here,\u8221\'94 Pyetle said. He shifted forward again, eager. He pointed with his finger. \u8220\'93Your witch, the old woman who was flattened by that red beast\hich\f0 \emdash \loch\f0 excuse me, I meant no disrespect, but she }{\f1\fs24\b0\i1 was}{\f0\fs24\b0\i0  flattened\hich\f0 \emdash \loch\f0 she was seer, no?\loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8221\'94}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 Ayram nodded.}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 \loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8220\'93I imagine you became accustomed to her fortune telling. Now that she is no longer here, you feel rudderless\hich\f0 \emdash \loch\f0 again, no disrespect intended, but you }{\f1\fs24\b0\i1 are}{\f0\fs24\b0\i0  forcing us all to sit here in this tenement of howling demons so that you can determine what to do.\loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8221\'94}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 Ayram glowered. \loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8220\'93Let\u8217\'92s take }{\f1\fs24\b0\i1 honest}{\f0\fs24\b0\i0  stock of our situation\loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8221\'94 he said, doubling Pyetle\u8217\'92s instruction and lacing it with venom. \u8220\'93All the gods are dead. That boy is the most powerful being in this world.\u8221\'94 He jabbed a strident finger in Mandri\u8217\'92s direction. \u8220\'93He has no limits! If he begins to eat, as the Burshageet eats, this world is doomed.\u8221\'94}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 Pyetle remained aloof. \loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8220\'93Mandri is powerful,\u8221\'94 he said, \u8220\'93but like any Mazid\hich\f0 \emdash \loch\f0 and I say this, assuredly, with no disrespect\hich\f0 \emdash \loch\f0 like any Mazid he can be overcome. Anyone can be caught surprised.\u8221\'94}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 \loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8220\'93Wrong,\u8221\'94 Ayram stated. \u8220\'93How can you surprise someone who can see the threads of fate? As well, he can cut them. He has the sight. The only way he dies, is if he desires it.\u8221\'94}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 Pyetle\loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8217\'92s eyebrows jumped. He opened his mouth to speak, then concern shaded his face, and he subsided.}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 \loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8220\'93Yes,\u8221\'94 Ayram said with ominous effect, \u8220\'93That was Mandri. When those demons were struck dumb in the comet\u8217\'92s chamber, that was Mandri.\u8221\'94}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 \loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8220\'93You\u8217\'92re saying he severed them from their fate?\u8221\'94}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 \loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8220\'93He can sever you from yours, me from mine. We should guess that he has already done it.\u8221\'94}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 Pyetle regarded Mandri with uncertainty.}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 \loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8220\'93It\u8217\'92s true,\u8221\'94 Mandri said to him, smiling in embarrassment of his power. \u8220\'93I mean, I haven\u8217\'92t cut your fate or anything, but I can see a certain future. I do not see far, but I do see it.\u8221\'94}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 He saw several white lines extending out of Sparks, strung across  room, portending movement. \loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8220\'93Those two Vessels there,\u8221\'94 he said, nodding to the the men standing guard against the temple exit, \u8220\'93one of them is going to be drawn towards us in a moment.\u8221\'94}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 \loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8220\'93Is he?\u8221\'94 Pyetle questioned. \u8220\'93What if I tell them both to go outside and stay there?\u8221\'94}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 \loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8220\'93I see what I see,\u8221\'94 Mandri said.}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 Pyetle beckoned to the Vessel standing close behind him. The man leaned down to receive his order.}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 \loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8220\'93Go tell those two by the exit to stand outside and stay there.\u8221\'94}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 The Vessel nodded, then did as Pyetle commanded. When he delivered the message, one of the watchmen headed outside, but the other\loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8217\'92s bright worldline led towards the fire, and he followed it. }
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 \loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8220\'93Sol\u8217\'92s light,\u8221\'94 Pyetle muttered as the man approached. \u8220\'93I told you to go outside!\u8221\'94}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 \loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8220\'93I wanted to thank  you,\u8221\'94 the Vessel said meekly. \u8220\'93In case we\u8230\'85I don\u8217\'92t know, I felt like I needed to thank all of you while you\u8217\'92re here.\u8221\'94 He gave a respectful bow, and then gave another bow meant for Mandri alone. \u8220\'93I owe you my life,\u8221\'94 he said.}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 \loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8220\'93Go on,\u8221\'94 Pyetle said, shooing the man away with stern glare.}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 The Vessel backed away, then hurried outside.}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 Pyetle bit his lip. \loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8220\'93I feel like I\u8217\'92ve been tricked.\u8221\'94}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 \loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8220\'93Think of how I feel,\u8221\'94 Mandri said. \u8220\'93I see all of your Sparks. If I focus, I can see your fates sprouting out of them. And I\u8217\'92m as enmeshed in all of this as you are. This brick of cappash in my hand has a little bit of fate connecting it to my mouth. I am going to eat this cappash, and I\u8217\'92m not sure my desire figures into it. Because I didn\u8217\'92t put that thread there, not knowingly.\u8221\'94}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 \loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8220\'93Can you cut that thread?\u8221\'94 Pyetle asked.}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 \loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8220\'93I can, but\u8230\'85\u8221\'94 Mandri took Elrahet\u8217\'92s Black knife out of his robe. He could see that hungry thread and knew he could cut it easily. The Black knife\u8217\'92s sheen dared him to do it. \u8220\'93But what about these thoughts of mine? Desire itself\hich\f0 \emdash \loch\f0 I can\u8217\'92t cut that. I mean, I can\u8217\'92t choose what I want to do, can I?\u8221\'94}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 Pyetle stroked his beard. \loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8220\'93You want to know if the action of cutting fate, is itself, fated?\u8221\'94}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 \loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8220\'93Yes.\u8221\'94}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 \loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8220\'93Well, what do these threads of fate look like?\u8221\'94}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 \loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8220\'93They look a bit like heavenly spit. They\u8217\'92re very bright. Some, less so. If I focus, I can see them describe every little action before it happens, like your fingers stroking your beard. And if I really focus, those lines get longer and I see further into the future. \u8221\'94}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 Pyetle stopped stroking his beard. He crossed his arms. \loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8220\'93Assuming you can cut these threads with that blade, the question becomes: do you see any threads of fate connected to that blade\u8217\'92s edge? That would mean something.\u8221\'94}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 \loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8220\'93I don\u8217\'92t think that\u8217\'92s possible,\u8221\'94 Mandri said. \u8220\'93The Black seems to hate these threads. I don\u8217\'92t think it can\u8230\'85\u8221\'94}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 He paused because there was chance that he wasn\loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8217\'92t focusing hard enough to see the threads attached to the knife.}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 He breathed deeply to gather his focus.}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 He stared at the knife. He immersed himself in its Black, beheld the ways it devoured the firelight even if its surface gleamed. Its edge was an absolute razor. The longer he stared, the more the world blurred world around it. It came alive. Its innervation zipped into his arm, into his chest, instilling in him a clangerous panic. He tried to drop the knife\hich\f0 \emdash \loch\f0 his grip tightened. Then the knife and the hand holding it doubled. Tripled. They jittered, then splayed out into a circular fan of hands holding knives, thousands of them, maybe uncountable, overlapping. He twisted his wrist, and all these blades turned together, a radial unfurling of the blackest flower with the sharpest of all possible petals.}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 Laced around the deadly fringe he saw, or thought he saw, a web of translucent threads. Almost invisible. If it was truly there, then it showed how each blade was connected to every other, and if it was truly fate, then it showed an infinite regress of effects acting out on an infinite regress of causes. He moved his infinite hands to cut these bindings, but each knife slipped past each thread to bend impossibly back around, a recursive swirl which severed themselves as well as the very notion of comprehensibility.}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 He gasped. He breathed deep. The action of his lungs expanding sucked him back into his skin.}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 \loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8220\'93Ayram,\u8221\'94 he said, a little woozy. \u8220\'93Did Elrahet see this end?\u8221\'94}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 \loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8220\'93She did not speak of ends,\u8221\'94 the giant grumbled. \u8220\'93I do. This dead prince does.\u8221\'94 }
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 Worms inside his skin.}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 \loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8220\'93This prince is a sign,\u8221\'94 Ayram said. \u8220\'93He was not put here by Elrahet, or Solraheen. He was put here by himself! Look at his courage! He did what needed doing! You must do the same!\u8221\'94}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 Mandri stares at the gaping hole in prince\loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8217\'92s abdomen, where the man had cut out his on Sparked stomach and then tossed into a fire. \u8220\'93I\u8217\'92m not going to do that,\u8221\'94 he said.}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 \loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8220\'93Mandri! Hear me!\u8221\'94 The force of Ayram\u8217\'92s indignation stood him up. He towered over all, a divine pillar of righteous fury. \u8220\'93Think of the destructive power of a man who is without equal; inviscerated with Solraheen\u8217\'92s light, but not His omniscience, or His benevolence. Such a man could only tempt this world\u8217\'92s fate. Why risk it?\u8221\'94}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 \loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8220\'93Good man,\u8221\'94 Pyetle cautioned with an open hand. \u8220\'93It would not be wise to\hich\f0 \emdash \loch\f0 \u8221\'94}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 \loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8220\'93Hear me!\u8221\'94 Ayram roared. \u8220\'93His life will end in his death, or ours!\u8221\'94}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 \loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8220\'93You don\u8217\'92t know that,\u8221\'94 Mandri said. \u8220\'93Even if you had the sight, you couldn\u8217\'92t know that.\u8221\'94}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 \loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8220\'93I have sight enough of }{\f1\fs24\b0\i1 you}{\f0\fs24\b0\i0 .\loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8221\'94}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 Ayram\loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8217\'92s deep voice crackled the fire. His frown imparted fear. His enmity challenged all.}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 Mandri chuckled. \loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8220\'93Elrahet once told me,\u8221\'94 he said softly, \u8220\'93that all she could do was convince me to try. Well, I\u8217\'92m going to listen to her; I\u8217\'92m going to try. You are going to have to deal with that.\u8221\'94}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 He chomped down on the cappash brick. He chewed with a sort of sighing ease that let Ayram know that this conversation was over.}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 After a moment\loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8217\'92s silence, Ayram sat back down.}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 They spent the rest of the night listening to demon howls while the fire burned down to ash. There was a little conversation about Pyetle\loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8217\'92s plan to carry news of these events back to Jeket. He wanted to take Mandri with him. Ayram was firmly against this, but he wasn\u8217\'92t for anything else.}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 Mandri, for his part, smiled. He smiled at how Pyetle saw in him something between a god and a long-lost brother, how Ayram saw in him a demon, how Moto, still mourning Moteah, hardly cared about him at all. Never before had he meant such disparate things to different people. And somehow, it didn\loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8217\'92t bother him.}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 \loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8220\'93I think I\u8217\'92ll go back to Meskalim,\u8221\'94 he said as first red of morning appeared outside. \u8220\'93I want to do something about a nasty leech farm out there.\u8221\'94}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 \loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8220\'93A leech farm!?\u8221\'94 Pyetle decried. \u8220\'93Mandri, there are more substantial problems for you to fix. Come with me to Jeket and I will\hich\f0 \emdash \loch\f0 \u8221\'94}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 \loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8220\'93No,\u8221\'94 Mandri said. \u8220\'93I\u8217\'92m going to do something about that damned farm.\u8221\'94}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 \loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8220\'93But there\u8217\'92s\hich\f0 \emdash \loch\f0 \u8221\'94}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 \loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8220\'93One thing at a time,\u8221\'94 Mandri sighed. \u8220\'93One thing at a time.\u8221\'94}}